Sinueux (i) by @williamapan and @christianelemieux

“Inspired by the sinuous fluidity of generative code, Art Nouveau and organic forms, this collaboration fuses the work of William Mapan and Christiane Lemieux in layers, texture, palette and form.
The pieces are created using multiple inputs of Lemieux’s traditional art, archival textiles and Mapan’s art and generative code. Each unique artwork from the series has a different visual signature.

Each NFT comes with a physical piece: a semi transparent printed textile. The organic experience is then transported seamlessly from the digital to the physical world.

Specifications of the physical piece: Width: 183,85cm, Height: 260cm, Weight: 700g” — William Mapan and Christiane Lemieux

Sinueux (i) is also on view in the “Digital Transcendence: The Intersection Between Art and Tech” exhibition at the SuperRare x 0x Gallery at @TheSeaportNYC until July 31.

In Ancient Greece, the birthplace of the wreath, originally worn as a crown - it was described as "the ornament of the priest in the performance of sacrifice, of the hero on his return from victory, of the bride at her nuptials, and of the guests at a feast." It also symbolized eternity, as the shape has no end. In the newer holiday manifestations of these ancient wreaths, equally important was the material forming the wreaths - the evergreen tree. Evergreen trees were a species looked upon with awe and admiration, since they, unlike most living things, survived the harshness of winter. The trees appeared in abundance in northern and eastern Europe, and people brought them into their homes.
That was a symbol to them of power, of resilience, and of hope. #lesdetailsfontladifférence #happyholidays
